12 Discriminant Analysis and Other Linear Classification Models

This is a tidymodels implementation of the code in Chapter 12 of Applied Predictive Modeling by Max Kuhn and Kjell Johnson1.

The authors use the Kaggle grant data set to demonstrate the models. I have chosen to demonstrate each model on a different data set in this notebook. The data set I have used is the Credit Approval Data Set which is available at the UCI Machine Learning Repository2. This data set is moderate in size (\(n = 653\), \(p = 16\)). It has a binary outcome variable which is relatively balanced. There is a mixture of categorical and numeric predictors, and only a small amount of missing data.

Each model is implemented in its own section, including preprocessing and tuning. The models are then collectively assessed in the Metrics section, which includes ROC curves and lift/gain charts for each model.

Setup

# Load packages:
library(tidyverse)
library(tidymodels)
library(discrim)
library(ggcorrplot)
library(patchwork)

# Load my functions:
source("/home/brian/R/dir/Util/bh_functions.R")

# Options:
theme_set(theme_bw())
options(digits = 4)

Load Data

# Prepare data:
df <- read_csv("/home/brian/R/dir/APM/chapter12/data/crx.data", col_names = F, na = '?') %>% 
  mutate(y = factor(X16),
         X11 = parse_number(X11),     # this should be continuous according to the description
         X14 = parse_number(X14)) %>% # this should be continuous according to the description
  # Using '+' and '-' causes problems for R so switch to simple strings;
  mutate(y = factor(if_else(y == "+", "yes", "no"), levels = c("yes", "no"))) %>% 
  # drop the original response, X16;
  dplyr::select(y, everything(), -X16)

# Remove missing data (small amount):
df <- na.omit(df)

# View data:
df

Data Splitting

# Splits
set.seed(1)
splits <- initial_split(df, strata = y) # default prop is 3/4
df_train <- training(splits)
df_test <- testing((splits))

# CV Folds:
set.seed(123)
folds <- vfold_cv(data = df_train, v = 5)

12.2 Logistic Regression

Preprocessing will be done via a recipe. No resampling is required. I will just fit() a model on the training data and make predictions on the test data.

Training data

# Preprocessing
rec1 <-
  recipe(y ~ ., data = df_train) %>% 
  step_center(all_numeric()) %>% 
  step_scale(all_numeric()) %>% 
  step_nzv(all_predictors()) %>% 
  step_corr(all_numeric(), threshold = 0.9) %>% 
  step_dummy(all_nominal(), -all_outcomes())

# Model
log_reg_mod <-
  logistic_reg() %>% 
  set_mode("classification") %>% 
  set_engine("glm")

# Workflow
workflow1 <- 
  workflow() %>% 
  add_recipe(rec1) %>% 
  add_model(spec = log_reg_mod)

# Fit
log_reg_fit <- 
  workflow1 %>% 
  fit(data = df_train)

# View fit:
# log_reg_fit %>% 
#   pull_workflow_fit()

Test data

# Fit final model and make predictions:
final_fit <- 
  workflow1 %>% 
  last_fit(splits)
! train/test split: preprocessor 1/1, model 1/1 (predictions): prediction from a rank-deficient fit may be misleading
# Collect predictions:
test_results <- 
  final_fit %>%
  collect_predictions()
test_results$model <- "Logistic Regression"

12.4 Partial Least Squares Discriminant Analysis

To implement PLSDA I believe I just have to preprocess the data to compute the PLS components. Then discriminant analysis is implemented as before. No resampling is used. I will fit() a model on the training data and make predictions on the test data.

Training

# Preprocessing
rec2 <-
  rec1 %>% 
  step_pls(all_numeric(), outcome = "y", num_comp = 3) # fix the no. of components at 3 for now (only 6 numeric variables)

# Model
plsda_mod <-
  discrim_linear() %>% 
  set_mode("classification") %>% 
  set_engine("MASS")

# Workflow
workflow3 <- 
  workflow() %>% 
  add_recipe(rec2) %>% 
  add_model(spec = plsda_mod)

# Fit
plsda_fit <- 
  workflow3 %>% 
  fit(data = df_train)

12.5 Penalized Models

Penalized Logistic Regression

This model is implemented by using the parameters penalty and mixture in the logistic_reg() function. The engine must be set to glmnet. I will use the same parameters that I used in the caret implementation. Use the same preprocessing as the logistic regression model.

Training data

# Model
pen_log_reg_mod <-
  logistic_reg(mixture = tune(), penalty = tune()) %>% 
  set_mode("classification") %>% 
  set_engine("glmnet")

# Workflow
workflow4 <- 
  workflow() %>% 
  add_model(spec = pen_log_reg_mod) %>% 
  add_recipe(rec1)

# Tuning grid
grid1 <- expand_grid(mixture = c(0, 0.2, 0.4, 0.6, 0.8, 1),
                     penalty = seq(0.01, 0.2, length = 40))

start <- bh_start_timer()
[1] "Start time: 2021-04-01 20:57:18"
# Tune
### Read in cached results if available:
file1 <- "/home/brian/R/dir/APM/chapter12/objects/pen_log_reg_res_clean.RDS"
if (file.exists(file1)) {
  pen_log_reg_res <- readRDS(file1)
} else {
  pen_log_reg_res <- 
    workflow4 %>% 
    tune_grid(resamples = folds, grid = grid1)
  saveRDS(pen_log_reg_res, file1)
}
end <- bh_end_timer()
[1] "End time: 2021-04-01 20:57:18"
bh_run_time(start, end)
[1] "Run time: 0.05 secs"
# Plot AUC tuning profile:
# Line plot:
p1 <- pen_log_reg_res %>% 
  autoplot(metric = "roc_auc") +
  ggsci::scale_color_nejm() +
  theme(legend.position = "top")

p2 <- pen_log_reg_res %>% 
  collect_metrics() %>% 
  filter(.metric == "roc_auc") %>% 
  ggplot() +
  geom_tile(aes(penalty, mixture, fill = mean)) +
  scale_y_continuous(breaks = seq(0, 1, 0.2)) +
  scale_fill_viridis_c() + # it looks better with the default direction
  coord_cartesian(expand = F) +
  labs(x = "Amount of Regularization (penalty)", y = "Proportion of lasso Penalty (mixture)", fill = "AUC")

p1 + p2 + plot_annotation(title = "Penalized Logistic Regression tuning parameter profile")

Test data

# Select best model:
best_mod <- pen_log_reg_res %>%
  select_best("roc_auc")

# Update final workflow:
final_wf <- 
  workflow4 %>% 
  finalize_workflow(best_mod)

# Fit final model and make predictions:
final_fit <- 
  final_wf %>%
  last_fit(splits)

# Collect predictions:
test_results <- 
  rbind(
    test_results,
    cbind(
      final_fit %>%
        collect_predictions(),
      model = "Penalized Logistic Regression"
    )
  )

Sparse LDA

There is as yet no implementation of sparse LDA in tidymodels.

Metrics

Calculate metrics

get_metrics <- function(test_results, model) {
  test_results <- test_results %>% 
    filter(model == {{ model }})
  
  metrics <- caret::confusionMatrix(data = test_results$.pred_class,
                                    reference = test_results$y,
                                    positive = "yes")
  
  metrics$auc <- 
    test_results %>% 
    yardstick::roc_auc(y, .pred_yes, event_level = "first") %>% # *1
    pluck(".estimate")
  
  return(metrics)
}

models <- unique(test_results$model)
metrics <- purrr::map(models, ~get_metrics(test_results, .x)) %>% 
  set_names(models)
Registered S3 method overwritten by 'data.table':
  method           from
  print.data.table     
# *1: event_level not required but added for clarity. It refers to the first level in the levels of the response. Since "yes" is the target and the first level, I have set those arguments here. It was different for the churn model in APM_12_exercise_12.3.Rmd because "yes" was the second level but the important thing is to be consistent. Same thing with the ROC curves and lift/gain charts below.

# Display a named list of metrics as a table as opposed to a vector:
bh_display_metric <- function(metrics, type = "Metric") { # metrics is a named vector of doubles
  M <- matrix(metrics)
  dimnames(M) <- list(names(metrics), type)
  return(M)
}

ROC Curves

# Returns an ROC curve for a given model:
plot_roc_curve <- function(test_results, model) {
  
  # Get AUC for labeling the plot:
  auc <- metrics[[{{ model }}]]$auc

  # ROC curve:
  p <- test_results %>% 
    filter(model == {{ model }}) %>% 
    yardstick::roc_curve(y, .pred_yes, event_level = "first") %>% 
    autoplot() +
    geom_label(aes(x = 0.75, y = 0.25, label = paste0("AUC:", round(auc, 3)))) +
    ggtitle(paste0("ROC - ", {{ model }})) +
    theme(plot.title = element_text(size = 10))
  return(p)
}

cowplot::plot_grid(
  plotlist = purrr::map(models, ~plot_roc_curve(test_results, .x))
)

Gain Curves

# Returns a gain curve for a given model:
plot_gain_curve <- function(test_results, model) {
  
  # Gain curve:
  p <- test_results %>% 
    filter(model == {{ model }}) %>% 
    yardstick::gain_curve(y, .pred_yes, event_level = "first") %>% 
    autoplot() +
    ggtitle(paste0("Gain - ", {{ model }})) +
    theme(plot.title = element_text(size = 10))
  return(p)
}

cowplot::plot_grid(
  plotlist = purrr::map(models, ~plot_gain_curve(test_results, .x))
)
